	<BR>
	<table width="100%">
		<tr valign="top">
			<td width="44%"> Resumo
			<div style="text-align:justify;">
				<P>
					<B>Introdução</B>: As micotoxinas são metabólitos secundários, produzidos por fungos que se desenvolvem naturalmente em produtos alimentícios, capazes de originar uma ampla variedade de efeitos tóxicos em animais vertebrados, incluindo o homem. As aflatoxinas são produzidas por fungos do gênero [e]lt;i[e]rt;Aspergillus[e]lt;/i[e]rt;. Atualmente, a aflatoxina B1 (AFB1) é uma das mais eficazes substâncias carcinogênicas, mutagênicas e teratogênicas e tem sido identificada como fator associado ao câncer hepático. Em peixes, a concentração de AFB1 pode desencadear diversos sinais clínicos inespecíficos. Os parâmetros bioquímicos nos peixes são considerados ferramentas de diagnóstico importantes para avaliar alterações metabólicas e de processos celulares.					<B>Objetivo</B>: The aim of this study was to determine the possible deleterious effects on silver catfish fed contaminated feed containing different levels of aflatoxin B1 (AFB1) by the biochemical parameters.					<B>Metodologia</B>: A total of 624 silver catfish fingerlings were used, with 08 weeks of life, randomly separated into 24 tanks (n = 26 fingerlings/aquarium), each group consisted of 06 tests aquariums (n = 156 fingerlings/group) and divided into four groups (GI – 0; GII – 45; GIII – 90 e GIV – 180 [e]#61549;g AFB1.kg-1 in feed) and they fed for 56 days. Blood samples were taken on days +28, +42 and +56 days of the experiment. They were dosed enzymes ALT, AST, ALP, GGT and albumin. For statistical analysis was used ANOVA followed by Bonferroni test or [e]lt;i[e]rt;Kruskal-Wallis[e]lt;/i[e]rt; test followed by [e]lt;i[e]rt;Dunn´s[e]lt;/i[e]rt; test.					<B>Resultados</B>: Foi observado um aumento significativo (p[e]lt;0,05) de FA do GIII em relação ao GIV no dia +42. Uma diminuição significativa (p[e]lt;0,05) de ALT dos GII, GIII e GIV em relação ao GI, no dia +56, e uma diminuição (p[e]lt;0,05) de FA e AST nos GIII e GIV em relação ao GI.					<B>Conclusões</B>: Pode-se concluir que as diferentes concentrações de AFB1 afetam negativamente os animais, podendo causar uma possível insuficiência hepática devido ao grande potencial hepatotóxico da AFB1.				</P>
			</div><B>Palavras-chave</B>: Enzimas hepáticas. Toxicidade. Peixes. Hepatotoxicidade. Micotoxinas.			<BR>
			<BR>
			</td><td width="2%">&nbsp;</td><td width="44%"> Abstract
			<div style="text-align:justify;">
				<P>
					<B>Introduction</B>: Mycotoxins are secondary metabolites produced by the fungi which develop naturally in food products, able to give a wide variety of toxic effects on vertebrates, including man. Aflatoxins are produced by [e]lt;i[e]rt;Aspergillus fungi[e]lt;/i[e]rt;. Currently, aflatoxin B1 (AFB1) is one of the most effective carcinogenic, mutagenic and teratogenic and has been identified as a factor associated with liver cancer. In fish, the concentration of AFB1 can produce many nonspecific clinical signs. Biochemical parameters in fish are considered important diagnostic tools to assess metabolic and cellular processes.					<B>Objectives</B>: The aim of this study was to determine the possible deleterious effects on silver catfish fed contaminated feed containing different levels of aflatoxin B1 (AFB1) by the biochemical parameters.					<B>Methods</B>: A total of 624 silver catfish fingerlings were used, with 08 weeks of life, randomly separated into 24 tanks (n = 26 fingerlings/aquarium), each group consisted of 06 tests aquariums (n = 156 fingerlings/group) and divided into four groups (GI – 0; GII – 45; GIII – 90 e GIV – 180 [e]#61549;g AFB1.kg-1 in feed) and they fed for 56 days. Blood samples were taken on days +28, +42 and +56 days of the experiment. They were dosed enzymes ALT, AST, ALP, GGT and albumin. For statistical analysis was used ANOVA followed by Bonferroni test or Kruskal-Wallis test followed by Dunn´s test.					<B>Results</B>: It observed a significant increase (p[e]lt;0.05) in ALP at GIII in relation to GIV on day +42. A significant decrease (p[e]lt;0.05) in ALT of GII, GIII and GIV in relation to GI on days +56, and a decrease (p[e]lt;0.05) ALP and AST in GIII and GIV in relation to GI.					<B>Conclusion</B>: It can be concluded that the different concentrations of AFB1 negatively affect animals, may cause a possible liver failure due to the great potential hepatotoxic of AFB1.				</P>
			</div><B>Keywords</B>: Liver enzymes. Toxicity. Fish. Hepatotoxicity. Mycotoxins.</td>
